Thanks for reaching out for deeper insights into the obstacles many of our immigrant neighbors are confronting. Below is a concise overview drawn from our recent Harmony Alliance meetings, direct conversations with families we serve, and supporting research:

1. Access to Health Care
   • Lack of insurance or limited coverage for the undocumented makes even basic care unattainable.
   • Language barriers and fear that medical records could be shared with immigration authorities deter people from seeking help.
   • Result: treat-able conditions become emergencies, increasing overall public-health costs.

2. Education for Children & Young Adults
   • K-12: Insufficient bilingual support and frequent relocations disrupt learning.
   • Higher Ed: Undocumented students are ineligible for most federal/state aid and, without DACA, risk removal while in school.
   • Parents often avoid school events because of ID requirements at the door, weakening home-school collaboration.

3. Legal Assistance
   • Genuine, affordable immigration attorneys are scarce; predatory “notarios” fill the gap and spread misinformation.
   • Many families lack clarity on their rights during workplace inspections or ICE actions.

4. Economic & Employment Pressures
   • Jobs are concentrated in low-wage sectors with little protection against wage theft or unsafe conditions.
   • Limited ability to secure professional licenses keeps skilled newcomers under-employed.

5. Food & Housing Insecurity
   • Recent surveys show 2 in 5 immigrant households in the city skipped meals last month. Our “Nourish Neighbors” drive is now feeding 50+ families weekly.
   • Overcrowding is common; fear of documentation checks prevents tenants from reporting hazardous living conditions.

6. Mental-Health Strain & Social Isolation
   • Trauma from past persecution compounded by the anxiety of potential separation from loved ones.
   • Stigma and cultural norms make professional counseling under-utilised even when sliding-scale clinics exist.

Promising Local Responses
• Community-based clinics (e.g., Elm Street Free Clinic) provide low-cost care with strict confidentiality protocols.
• "Know Your Rights" workshops offered monthly by the Legal Aid Society demystify interactions with law enforcement.
• The city school district’s new Family Liaison program is expanding Spanish and Mandarin translation services.

